parent.name: Sun
parent.description: The center of our solar system, the Sun provides the energy needed for life on Earth, and its gravitational influence keeps the planets in orbit.

planets.name: Mercury
planets.description: The smallest and closest planet to the Sun, Mercury's lack of atmosphere means its surface is extremely hot during the day and freezing at night.

planets.name: Venus
planets.description: Often called Earth’s “twin” due to its similar size, Venus is covered by thick clouds of sulfuric acid, making it the hottest planet in the solar system.

planets.name: Earth
planets.description: The third planet from the Sun, Earth is the only known planet to support life.

planets.name: Mars
planets.description: The 'Red Planet' has captured human imagination due to its potential for past life and its role as the most accessible planet for human exploration.

planets.name: Jupiter
planets.description: The gas giant is so massive that its gravity helps shape the solar system, and its immense magnetic field protects Earth from space debris.

planets.name: Saturn
planets.description: The ringed planet is known for its stunning beauty and complex system of moons and rings.

planets.name: Uranus
planets.description: The seventh planet from the Sun is an icy giant, known for its tilted axis and thin atmosphere.

planets.name: Neptune
planets.description: The eighth planet from the Sun is an icy giant, known for its strong winds and few moons.
